  title         = {Differenzierendes zu Jonas' Konzept der Verantwortung},
  number        = {1-2},
  pages         = {153-172},
  volume        = {18},
  abstract      = {It is evident that ethics, if one takes into account the
pragmatic conditions of its application in the world that
constantly changes, cannot remain static; rather, it must
assume a stance with respect to both the changeable
possibilities of action and the potentials of the
side-effects in the field of the technologically
accomplishable, and it must make sure that it does not
simply adjust to these changes. The constant fundamental
ethical impulses can and must--considering that the
applicability of the central ethical concepts (Jonas's
parental responsibility) has been fully widened, and that
all ethical judgment of the side-effects, which can not
possibly be fully anticipated (due to which more cautious,
stricter inferences are necessary, while at the same time
all risks cannot or should not be avoided) has become more
sensitive--pragmatically assume a stance in relation to the
present situation of Homo Faber technologicus. (edited)},
