  date          = {1999},
  title         = {Criticality and scaling in evolutionary ecology},
  number        = {4},
  pages         = {156-160},
  volume        = {14},
  abstract      = {Fluctuations in ecological systems are known to involve a
wide range of spatial and temporal scales, often displaying
self similar (fractal) properties. Recent theoretical
approaches are trying to shed light on the nature of these
complex dynamics. The results suggest that complexity in
ecology and evolution comes from the network-like structure
of multispecies communities that are close to instability.
If true, these ideas might change our understanding of how
complexity emerges in the biosphere and how
macroevolutionary events could be decoupled from
microevolutionary ones.},
