  author    = {STARCK, D.},
  date      = {1962},
  title     = {The present stand of the fetalization problem},
  number    = {(2)},
  pages     = {129--155},
  volume    = {77},
  abstract  = {-This is a critical discussion of the Bolk hypothesis
(1926) in the light of new osteological research. It is
shown that special characters of body form, caused by
changes in size and type of growth are not correlated. The
principle of fetalization is considered of no value as a
general law of domestication. A comparison of the evolution
in man and other primates indicates processes of
acceleration as well as those of retardation and deviation.
It is demonstrated that the special skull form of dwarf
dogs is different from that of puppies and fromnormal size
dogs. Brachycephaly is considered to be not in consequence
of dwarfism. || ABSTRACT AUTHORS: G. F. W. Haenlein},
